<h2>What Is GEO (Generative Engine Optimization)?</h2>
<p><a href="/blog/what-is-geo/">GEO</a> is the practice of optimizing content so that large language models (LLMs) cite, reference, or surface it in their AI-generated responses. GEO targets platforms like ChatGPT, Perplexity, Google Gemini, Claude, and Microsoft Copilot.</p>
<h3>How GEO Works</h3>
<p>Generative AI models work differently from search engines. They do not show a list of links. They synthesize information from multiple sources into a single response. When a user asks ChatGPT "What is the best SEO strategy for a local business?" the model pulls from its training data and, increasingly, from real-time web retrieval to construct an answer.</p>
<p>Getting cited in that answer requires:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Topical authority</strong> ,  <a href="/blog/what-is-topical-authority/">Deep coverage</a> of a subject across multiple pages, not just one thin article</li>
<li><strong>Factual density</strong>. Specific numbers, data points, named sources, and original research</li>
<li><strong>Structured formatting</strong>. Clear headings, definition-lead sentences, and well-organized sections that LLMs can parse</li>
<li><strong>Source credibility</strong>. Mentions across multiple trusted platforms (Wikipedia, industry publications, authoritative directories)</li>
<li><strong>AI crawler access</strong>. Allowing <a href="/blog/ai-crawlers-guide/">AI crawlers</a> (GPTBot, ClaudeBot, PerplexityBot) to access your content</li>
</ul>
<p>The research behind GEO comes from a 2024 Georgia Tech, Princeton, and IIT Delhi study that tested optimization strategies across 10,000 queries. They found that adding statistics improved AI citation rates by 30-40%, and that authoritative, well-structured content consistently outperformed keyword-stuffed pages.</p>
