<h2>Common Mistakes When Combining GEO, AEO, and SEO</h2>
<h3>Mistake 1: Blocking AI Crawlers</h3>
<p>Some businesses block GPTBot, ClaudeBot, and other AI crawlers in their <code>robots.txt</code> file. This prevents your content from appearing in AI responses entirely. Unless you have a specific licensing reason to block AI access, allow these crawlers. Read our <a href="/blog/ai-crawlers-guide/">AI crawlers guide</a> for details on each crawler and how to configure access.</p>
<h3>Mistake 2: Choosing One Strategy Over the Others</h3>
<p>GEO is not a replacement for SEO. AEO is not a replacement for either. Businesses that abandon SEO fundamentals to chase AI citations will lose both channels. SEO provides the indexed, authoritative content base that AEO and GEO depend on.</p>
<h3>Mistake 3: Ignoring Structured Data</h3>
<p><a href="/glossary/schema-markup/">Schema markup</a> serves all three strategies. FAQ schema helps answer engines. Article and Organization schema helps AI models understand your content. Product schema helps both. Skipping structured data means leaving performance gains on the table across every channel.</p>
<h3>Mistake 4: Writing for Keywords Only</h3>
<p>Keyword-optimized content ranks in search engines. But answer engines need clear, concise answers. And AI models need factual density, statistics, and authoritative sourcing. Content that only targets keywords without addressing these additional needs will rank but will not get featured or cited.</p>
<h3>Mistake 5: No Original Data</h3>
<p>AI models have access to millions of pages that say the same thing. Content with original statistics, proprietary data, or unique research stands out. If every competitor publishes "10 SEO tips" with the same recycled advice, the AI model has no reason to cite yours over theirs. Give it a reason.</p>
